				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">I don't know what you're talking about, but Super Mario Bros. runs the entire game as an NMI handler. After the init code, SMB's main thread is running the following code, which emulators running on handhelds (e.g. PocketNES and PocketNES) will usually automatically detect as a speed hack:
<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">:<br />&nbsp; jmp :-<br /></div><br />The easiest way to convert $2002 spinning code to NMI based code uses a variable in RAM:<br /><div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">.segment &quot;ZEROPAGE&quot;<br />retraces: .res 1<br /><br />.segment &quot;CODE&quot;<br />nmiHandler:<br />&nbsp; inc retraces<br />&nbsp; rti<br /><br />; In main loop:<br />&nbsp; lda retraces<br />:<br />&nbsp; cmp retraces<br />&nbsp; beq :-<br /><br /></div></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

